her game in a hunting park; compare   Parker  .","occupational name denoting the servant (Middle English <i>man</i>) of someone called <i>Park</i> (see   Park   2)."]},{"name":"Parkerson","meanings":["English: from the occupational name   Parker   + patronymic <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Parkey","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): dialect pronunciation of   Parker  . <i>Parker</i> has a long history in Macclesfield, Manchester, and Bridgnorth."]},{"name":"Park","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Sang, Sung, Yong, Jung, Jong, Chan, Jae, Jin, Kwang, Kyung, Myung, Chong, Chang, Chung, Byung, Min, Moon, Chul, Hae, Jeong, Dae, Seong, Myong.","English and Scottish: from Middle English and Older Scots <i>parc</i>, <i>parke</i>, <i>perk</i> ‘park, enclosure’ (Old French <i>parc</i>), often referring to the grounds of a manor house or a deer park where the lord hunted. The name was probably synonymous with   Parker  , denoting an officer who looked after a park for the lord of the manor.","English and Scottish: from a medieval pet form of the personal name   Peter  . Compare   Parkin  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":12,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":21,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":66,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Parker was born in 1316, in England as the daughter of William Parker. She had at least 1 son with Hugh Croft."},"et":{"1316–":"1316–Surnud","1316–Female":"1316–Surnud","1306–1370":"1306–1370","1336–1375":"1336–1375","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1453":"1453","1375":"1375","1284":"1284","1382":"1382",